            <pb facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <p><hi rendition="#k">Opinion of Humboldt.</hi>&#x2014;The opinion of<lb/>
                    Baron Humboldt upon &#x201C;moving tables&#x201D; is<lb/>
                    found in the Dresden Journal. According to a<lb/>
                    communication in that paper, Humboldt writes<lb/>
                    Dr. Franz Schlegel, M. D. of Altenburgh, in<lb/>
                    relation to two treatises upon &#x201C;moving tables&#x201D;<lb/>
                    by the Doctor. A translation of the Baron&#x2019;s let-<lb/>
                    ter is as follows:</p>
                <lb/>
                <p>&#x201C;It is easier to combat a theory than facts<lb/>
                    imperfectly observed. There are diseases of<lb/>
                    belief which return periodically, and are as en-<lb/>
                    demical with the polished as with the lower<lb/>
                    classes, because in the former they assume the<lb/>
                    form of dogmatism and arrogance peculiar to<lb/>
                    the superficial. I tender you, most honored<lb/>
                    doctor, my kindest thanks for the publication<lb/>
                    of your very simple mechanical explanation of<lb/>
                    the turning of tables towards the north pole.<lb/>
                    But you will convert nobody.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">With the highest esteem, &amp;c.<lb/>
                            ALEXANDER VON HUMBOLDT.
                        </hi>
                    </salute>
                </closer>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Berlin,</hi> April 18, 1853.</dateline>
            </div>
            <lb/>
        </body>
